# Build the Neat-Memory DM

## Step

Joel's ask (2026-07-16, verbatim): "we have joelclaw messages and the
ability to send messages, it'd be cool if 'neat/awesome memories' got
sent occasionally from the observer/gardner."

A push surface: the observer family occasionally DMs Joel one memory
from the distilled layer that's genuinely neat — a delight, not a
digest. Resolved when a daily check runs from the observer's home
(joelclaw-observer, LaunchAgent), most days sends nothing, and when it
does send, the DM reads like a friend saying "remember this?" with a
working link.

Design decisions (steering, 2026-07-16):

- **Cadence**: one LaunchAgent check per day; at most ONE DM per day,
  and only when a candidate clears the quality bar — silence is the
  default. "Occasionally" means the bar does the pacing, not a schedule.
- **Candidates**: observation pages in
  `dark-wizard/.brain/observations/` from the last 7 days.
  `privacy: sensitive` pages are excluded before any model sees them —
  fails closed on missing/unparseable frontmatter.
- **Neatness is pi judgment behind a versioned schema** (house
  pattern): score + one-line "why it's neat" in Joel's plain voice;
  threshold gates the send. No send on judge failure — fail silent to
  the DM channel, loud to the log.
- **Dedupe forever**: sent slugs recorded in
  `~/.joelclaw/observer-neat-memories.json` (0600); a page DMs once,
  ever.
- **Delivery**: `joelclaw notify send --priority low` with the one-liner
  plus the canonical URL `https://brain.joelclaw.com/user/observations/<slug>`
  — only if that exact URL returns HTTP 200 at send time; otherwise the
  DM carries the page path instead of a dead link.
- **Receipts**: every run logs candidates seen / judged / sent to its
  own log; the send envelope must be ok before the dedupe entry is
  written.

## Amendment — grilling (Joel, 2026-07-16)

Four calls that supersede parts of the design above:

1. **"Neat" is four flavors, all in**: delight/surprise ("ha, I forgot
   about that"), milestones & wins, useful resurfacing (still
   actionable / about to matter again), and system self-awareness (the
   fleet noticing its own interesting behavior). The judgment carries a
   `flavor` tag; the DM can be any of them.
2. **Corpus widens**: observations + dream rollups + retros (retros
   live outside the observations dir — privacy gate handles each source
   explicitly, fails closed per source).
3. **Pacing is the curator's judgment, not a rule** (supersedes the
   fixed ≥8 threshold as the pacing mechanism): the smartest available
   agent decides send/hold given candidates + send history. Joel
   authorized API spend for Fable via `claude -p` for this specific use
   case; `gpt-5.6-sol:xhigh` via pi is the other serious config. The
   real artifact is the curator's **taste skill** — a versioned file
   defining what Joel finds neat, which the judge reads before judging.
   Judge configs (model × skill) must be **benchable** so Joel can see
   and feel what he likes → graduated to
   [Bench the Curator](./bench-neat-memory-curator.svx). Max 1 DM/day
   stays as a dumb safety cap under whatever the curator decides.
4. **Reactions teach taste**: each sent entry records an `outcome`
   (null until graded); graded sends accumulate as worked/didn't
   examples the taste skill cites — the skill is living, not static.
   V1 builds the schema; reaction-capture plumbing is its own later
   step.
